         <h1>Emil Fackenheim, 87, Scholar Of Judaism and the Holocaust </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Emil Ludwig Fackenheim , a German-born philosopher and Jewish theologian who sought to place the Holocaust in the context of Judaism , died on Sept. 19 in Jerusalem , where he had lived after retiring from the University of Toronto in 1984 . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 87 . <br><blue>3</blue>Dr. Fackenheim narrowly escaped from Germany in 1939 and spent much of his working life in Canada trying to come to terms with what befell European Jews in that era . <br><blue>4</blue>He chronicled that personal and intellectual journey in his latest book , '' An Epitaph for German Judaism : From Halle to Jerusalem . '' <br><blue>5</blue>An autobiography , it is scheduled to be published this year . <br><blue>6</blue>( Halle was the city of his birth in Germany . ) <br><blue>7</blue>Professor Fackenheim investigated the essential meaning of Judaism in order to come to terms with the Holocaust . <br><blue>8</blue>To him , the Holocaust became a rationale for Jewish survival . <br><blue>9</blue>He emphasized this in his often-cited appeals to Jews not to grant Hitler posthumous victories by forgetting , or by assimilating . <br><blue>10</blue>In his view , Jewish survival must be the paramount concern for Jews today . <br><blue>11</blue>The evolution of his thinking manifested itself in numerous articles and books , many still in print , including '' What Is Judaism ? <br><blue>12</blue>An Interpretation for the Present Age '' ( Syracuse University Press , 1999 ) ; '' The God Within : Kant , Schelling and Historicity '' ( University of Toronto Press , 1996 ) ; '' Jewish Philosophers and Jewish Philosophy '' ( Indiana University Press , 1996 ) ; '' To Mend the World : Foundations of Post-Holocaust Jewish Thought '' ( Indiana , 1993 ) ; '' The Jewish Bible After the Holocaust : A Re-Reading '' ( Indiana , 1991 ) ; and '' The Religious Dimension in Hegel 's Thought '' ( University of Chicago ; reprinted 1982 ) . <br><blue>13</blue>He received his early education in Halle . <br><blue>14</blue>He studied Judaism under Leo Baeck at the Hochschule für die Wissenschaft des Judentums in Berlin , and in 1937 he was the last Jewish student allowed to enroll at Martin Luther University in Halle . <br><blue>15</blue>But he resumed his rabbinical studies in Berlin the following year . <br><blue>16</blue>Arrested after the Nazi pogrom of Nov. 9 , 1938 -- Kristallnacht -- he spent three months in a concentration camp outside Berlin . <br><blue>17</blue>He was released on the condition that he leave the country . <br><blue>18</blue>He managed to pass his rabbinical examinations and was ordained in Berlin before fleeing the country . <br><blue>19</blue>He pursued his doctoral studies at the University of Aberdeen and was detained as an enemy alien of military age and deported to Canada , where he spent time in a prison camp in Quebec before gaining refuge . <br><blue>20</blue>He earned a doctorate in philosophy at the University of Toronto in 1945 and served as the rabbi to a congregation in Hamilton , Ontario , before he joined the university faculty in 1948 . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>An autobiography</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (5_4) 	<br><blue>2(12)</blue>: <m_str>Halle</m_str> (14_35) 	<m_str>itself</m_str> (11_7) 	<m_str>Halle</m_str> (13_7) 	<m_str>Hitler</m_str> (9_13) 	<m_str>Halle</m_str> (6_2) 	<m_str>Halle</m_str> (4_21) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (8_2) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_2) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (6_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (9_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_4) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>Germany</m_str> (6_10) 	<m_str>Germany</m_str> (3_6) 	<br><blue>4(4)</blue>: <m_str>the Holocaust</m_str> (1_15) 	<m_str>the Holocaust</m_str> (12_74) 	<m_str>the Holocaust</m_str> (7_16) 	<m_str>the Holocaust</m_str> (8_4) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>the University of Aberdeen</m_str> (19_7) 	<m_str>the University of Toronto in 1945</m_str> (20_8) 	<br><blue>6(4)</blue>: <m_str>Berlin</m_str> (15_8) 	<m_str>Berlin</m_str> (16_23) 	<m_str>Berlin</m_str> (14_16) 	<m_str>Berlin</m_str> (18_12) 	<br><blue>7(2)</blue>: <m_str>1996</m_str> (12_48) 	<m_str>1996</m_str> (12_33) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>the country</m_str> (18_15) 	<m_str>the country</m_str> (17_10) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>Indiana</m_str> (12_64) 	<m_str>Indiana</m_str> (12_81) 	<br><blue>10(2)</blue>: <m_str>his rabbinical studies</m_str> (15_4) 	<m_str>his doctoral studies</m_str> (19_3) 	<br><blue>11(16)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (13_3) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_2) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_21) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_4) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (19_3) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (17_8) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_28) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (18_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_14) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_27) 	<br><blue>12(2)</blue>: <m_str>Jerusalem</m_str> (4_23) 	<m_str>Jerusalem</m_str> (1_28) 	<br><blue>13(4)</blue>: <m_str>Judaism under Leo Baeck at the Hochschule für</m_str> (14_3) 	<m_str>Judaism</m_str> (11_23) 	<m_str>Judaism</m_str> (1_21) 	<m_str>Judaism</m_str> (7_8) 	<br><blue>14(7)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (1_31) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_13) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Dr. Fackenheim</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>Professor Fackenheim</m_str> (7_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_9) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
